# Priority Assignment (How LOW / MEDIUM / HIGH / CRITICAL is decided)

An issue's `priority` is set by **exactly two inputs** — nothing else changes it.

## 1. Initial AI suggestion (once, at creation)

When a **new** Issue is created, Gemini (`src/lib/ai/analyze-report.ts`) reads the report's
title, description, and category and returns a `priority` (`LOW | MEDIUM | HIGH | CRITICAL`) plus
a one-sentence `priorityReason`. If the AI call fails, the issue defaults to `MEDIUM`. This is
the only judgment-based step and it happens once, at creation. The reason may be shown; the
priority is shown as a badge — **never as a "% confidence"**.

## 2. Arithmetic auto-elevation by report volume

As duplicate reports cluster onto an issue, `computeImpact(reportCount)` (`src/lib/utils.ts`)
raises priority purely by count:

| Reports on the issue | Floor priority |
|---|---|
| ≥ 8  | HIGH |
| ≥ 15 | CRITICAL |

Applied in `attachReportToIssue` via `maxPriority(current, elevated)` — it **only ever raises**
priority, never lowers a higher existing value. This is the ONE place arithmetic changes
priority without a human, and it is defensible because it is a count of affected citizens, not
a prediction.

## What does NOT change priority

- Community verification and resolution disputes — independent of priority.
- The age/attention flags (`needsAttention`) — factual age only, never touch priority.
- There is **no manual priority editor** in the UI today. (If one is added, it should use
  `maxPriority` semantics so a human can raise but the system never silently overrides a human.)

**Code:** AI suggestion → `analyze-report.ts`; elevation → `computeImpact` + `maxPriority` in
`utils.ts`; both applied in `createNewIssueFromReport` (initial) and `attachReportToIssue`
(elevation) in `src/lib/actions/reports.ts`.

